@balenciaga is heading to New York for its latest campaign, A New York Minute, directed by Oscar-nominated filmmaker @helloellephanta and starring actor @sarah__pidgeon. Launching May 27, the campaign is made up of three one-minute films shot across Manhattan, following Pidgeon through everyday city moments that slowly reveal themselves to be carefully staged movie sets. Alongside looks from Balenciaga’s Fall 2026 collection, the films spotlight the House’s Le City, Le 7 Bowling, and Rodeo bags.⁠
⁠
The campaign also spills onto Instagram through @keeppprolling, a dedicated account sharing behind-the-scenes images and off-duty moments captured by Pierpaolo Piccioli, Monaris, and Zora Sicher. Featuring collaborators from Song’s filmmaking circle, including Past Lives cinematographer Shabier Kirchner, the project plays with the line between fiction and reality while turning the chaos of New York into part of the story itself.

@gucci has signed a multi-year deal as title partner of the @alpinef1team Team, which from 2027 will race under the name Gucci Racing Alpine Formula 1 Team. The partnership also launches Gucci Racing, a new platform spanning content, products and exclusive experiences at the intersection of luxury and sport.⁠
⁠
Calling the move “very bold, very Gucci,” president and CEO Francesca Bellettini said the collaboration goes far beyond logo placement, with creative director Demna actively involved in shaping the project. The deal further highlights fashion’s growing presence in Formula 1, alongside brands including Louis Vuitton, Tommy Hilfiger, Adidas and Puma.

@stussy latest seasonal rollout proves the Californian streetwear pioneer is thinking far beyond oversized tees and checkered shirting. Alongside its Spring/Summer 2026 apparel, the brand is quietly assembling a lineup of unexpectedly desirable lifestyle objects: stainless steel strainers, pool-shaped ceramic trays, branded frisbees, beach towels, and more. What first reads like randomness quickly reveals itself as a return to one of streetwear’s oldest tricks: turning everyday objects into collectible design pieces through the power of a logo.⁠
⁠
The accessory push extends into collaborations, too. Stüssy recently linked with German penmaker Kaweco on a sleek aluminium ballpoint pen and teamed up with storage manufacturer THOR on logo-heavy bins and containers. The move recalls the spirit of Stüssy Livin’ General Store, the brand’s now-defunct homeware imprint that spent the 2010s stamping surf-adjacent cool onto furniture, coffee makers, and household essentials. A decade later, with Stüssy firmly re-established as one of fashion’s most influential labels, the branded domestic oddities are making a timely comeback.

@coach and @wearebraindead carnival-like collab arrives just as the fashion world threatens to move on from trinket maximalism, doubling down instead on charms, plush mascots, pins, patches, and all things ornamented. Debuting via a surprise flash runway in NYC’s Meatpacking District, the collection spans retro womenswear, vintage sportswear-inspired menswear, leather goods, and accessories overloaded with fictional cartoon mascots, glossy plastic charms, and souvenir-style graphics. Think O-ring suede jackets jangling with keychains, bias-cut gingham skirts, rugby polos, mesh jerseys, and bags practically buried beneath adornments.⁠
⁠
For Brain Dead co-founder Kyle Ng and Coach Creative Director Stuart Vevers, the project became less about individual products and more about building a fully immersive universe inspired by Tokyo street style, ‘90s revivals of ‘70s fashion, theme park souvenirs, and Y2K-era collectible culture. The result feels intentionally chaotic in the spirit of FRUiTS Magazine, where personalization, humor, and nostalgia collide. Standouts like the plush pink bear bag, charm-covered Tabby, and cartoon lunchbox bags prove the collab’s biggest success lies in its accessories, making a convincing argument that fashion’s obsession with trinkets is far from over.

@DVF annuncia @HenryZankov come nuovo Direttore Artistico della maison — in questo ruolo supervisionerà l’intera identità creativa del brand, dalle collezioni alla visual identity. Il suo debutto è atteso per settembre 2026 alla New York Fashion Week. Un nuovo capitolo per una delle case americane più iconiche.
